There is much more to a multiplatform approach than you state here.  The
costs are very high and you need a different skill set throughout the company.
Development is different, QA is different, tech support is different -- even
marketing is different.  Some of the markets are so small that it isn't a
good return on investment.  Developing for those other platforms isn't any
sort of insurance, because they can't provide the revenue that Windows does.
If a company like Corel or Borland was forced out of Windows, they'd have
to cut a huge percentage of their workforce.

