Lotus hasn't upgraded their Windows products in some time.  Of course they're
behind.  They have been spending a lot of time and energy on OS/2, though,
and that fact was totally ignored by the analysts that caused their stock
to plunge.  Lotus is in trouble because they haven't upgraded their Windows
products in a long time, and because the Windows upgrades they've promised 
have all slipped.

>Borland is no longer a serious competitor to MS in productivity products.  

If you count databases as productivity products, then you're wrong.  If you
don't, then, other than SideKick, we don't *have* any productivity products.

>MS has cornered the market.  The question is, did they do it fairly or not?

No, the reality is that they haven't cornered the market at all.  Sure,
Word sells more copies than WordPerfect on Windows, and Excel sells more
copies than 1-2-3.  But both WordPerfect and 1-2-3 sell more copies 
individually than all OS/2 spreadsheets and word processors put together.

